@node Intro "ADB`s Games Volume 3 - Introduction"


      This is my 3rd games release for the Amiga - though perhaps
      misleading since the ABI Encoder and Decoder programs are not
      games!

     @{" Games Vol. 1 " link GV1} - Games Volume 1 (Alutia's Jewels and Breaker)
     @{" Games Vol. 2 " link GV2} - Games Volume 2 (BLIAM! and Simple Art 2004)

@endnode

@node GV1 "ADB's Games Volume 3 - Introduction / Games Volume 1"

      My first games release included 2 games - Alutia`s Jewels and
      Breaker.

      Alutia's Jewels was my first game I made for the Amiga and is a
      simple maze game where the aim is to work your way through to
      get to the Jewel at the end of each stage.
      Being my first game, made back in 2003, it has no sound (!) and
      very simple graphics. This got me hooked on programming again and
      shortly after finishing this (and after my brother moved out) I
      was able to start work on my second game, Breaker.

      Breaker is a clone of a game that was found in the back of my
      Spectrum 128K manual, called Bustout.
      A very simple game at heart, all you do is move the bat to keep
      the ball in play and destroy the bricks to score points. Once
      the target score has been achieved you were able to move on to the
      next stage (of which there are 15) by pressing the relevant key
      on the keyboard or by letting the ball go out of play.

      This is my first (and only) game so far to feature a working
      scoreboard, which is saved onto the disk. Also hidden away is a
      file that stores your total game time (up to a maximum of 999
      days, 23 hours, 59 minutes and 59 seconds!) which was inspired
      by a similar stats feature included on many of Sega`s Saturn
      games.

@endnode

@node GV2 "ADB's Games Volume 3 - Introduction / Games Volume 2"

      My 2nd games release featured one game called BLIAM! and an art
      program called Simple Art 2004.

      Work on BLIAM! began back around Sept/Oct 2004 and was to be my
      3rd piece of software written for the Amiga using AMOS. This game
      turned into something slightly different to what I had planned,
      but either way it was to be a puzzle game.

      This was my first program to feature music by myself aswell as a
      cool piece of music by M. Brown (aka SPADGE). My music skills
      were fairly limited, but not bad for my first attempt! Hopefully
      my composing skills will get better with time.

      I originally planned to make 50 levels, but after 4 months of
      solid development (and some programmers block!) I found that
      most of the new levels I had designed were too similar to those
      already in the game. If you want more levels feel free to @{"contact" link ContactMe}
      @{"me" link ContactMe} requesting more levels - perhaps throw in some suggestions and
      get your name in the credits!

      After fixing a few bugs and re-writing the code to optimise speed
      BLIAM! was finally finished by 31st December 2004.


      Simple Art 2004 (SA2004) was, surprisingly, originally written
      early in 2004 and was only for my personal use.

      However, the file selector was no more than an INPUT command and
      there was no way of viewing files already on the disk (or the
      harddrive) and a few other things needed improving too.

      I had hoped to have the improved version of SA2004 finished by
      the end of February 2005, but I kept on finding bugs which needed
      fixing.

      With the addition of a few features and having improved it I felt
      that I could include it on this disk for others to use. I realise
      that it doesn`t have many of the features that professional art
      packages have, but it was only meant to be a simple art program.

      Although it is just an art program, I have included the option
      to load in AMOS (.abk) music bank files. Since there wasn`t
      enough space on the Games Volume 2 disk, I included an extra
      disc which contained all the AMOS music files I had at the time.
      Most, if not all, are by M. Brown (aka SPADGE) and not myself
      sadly - though I have used them in my own games until I can
      write some decent music :)

      Feel free to @{"contact me" link ContactMe} with suggestions on how it could be
      improved and you may just find your name on the credits of
      Simple Art 2005 (which may not be finished until 2006!).

@endnode

@node ABI_Enc "ADB's Games Volume 3 - ABI Encoder"

      The ABI format was a brainwave I had back in June/July 2005. At
      first it started out as just an experiment as I didn't expect it
      to create files that are, most of the time, smaller than the
      standard IFF image format.

      Once I had the format down on paper, it took me a few months to
      code up the Encoder and Decoder files. Both were finished by
      October, but I still had the introduction file to write and
      (thanks to Karsten Schenk) I got distracted by some new AMOS
      Extensions I had, among other things.
      The introduction file was finally written in December and made
      use of the 3D letters I had modelled earlier in the year when
      experimenting with AMOS's 3D Object Modeller program.

      I hope that you will find this program useful, it converts IFF
      images into my ABI image format. I suggest you try it with
      the Turbo Mode on atleast once, as it can speed up the program
      by up to 25%! However, it can sometimes crash your Amiga! :(


@endnode

@node ABI_Dec "ADB's Games Volume 3 - ABI Decoder"

      The ABI Decoder program is used to convert ABI images back to
      the standard IFF format.
      This will be useful for those of you that use my forthcoming
      Simple Art 2006 art program which will be out sometime around
      Autumn 2006. I fully intend it to use both the IFF and ABI file
      formats.


@endnode

@node ImagesF "ADB's Games Volume 3 - Images Folder"

      This folder contains various demo images, with most in both IFF
      and ABI format for you to compare.
      All images starting with "VL" are by Vicky Lavington and, possibly,
      some of her mates (Kerry and Louise, among others).


@endnode

